    "pageContentHtml": "<h1>Empathy is a Verb</h1>\n<p>Where does our contemporary inclination toward &quot;user-centred-ness&quot; fit in the history of design, innovation, and industrialization?  How does historical context condition our understanding of the &quot;human&quot; in &quot;human centred design&quot;?  Part of the answer is the three perspectives on human: humans as users of what we design, humans as the people doing the design, and humanity as the inhabitants of the planet where what is designed gets made and used.  This session fills in some of the time line stretching from the reformers, innovation enthusiasts, and industrialists of mid 19th century to us at the start of the 21st.  </p>\n<p>This is meant to be a fast - and unreasonable - romp through 150-170 years of history.  We will not be giving anything the attention it deserves; our goals are two: to come out with a sense of the trajectory and a hunger to make further exploration of the history of design a part of our professional training; (2) to focus on two cases that strongly influence how we think about the role of design vis a vis industry and society (Bauhaus and Ulm).   </p>\n<p>Start listening to the BBC piece on the Great Exhibition and view the short video on utilitarianism. Then start reading the selections in McDermott.  You might start with the one you are assigned, but be sure to visit the others.  Watch at least one of the &quot;Bauhaus World&quot; videos, read about ULM, and watch some of Pelle Ehn&#39;s lecture, look at the PARC timeline and then at least the shortest of the IDEO videos. </p>\n<p>You have two concrete assignments related to this history material.  After you have finished the readings and viewings, create a <a href=\"https://q.utoronto.ca/courses/136326/pages/visualizing-the-readings\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">first draft mind map</a> that has your assigned topic at the center. You can include as many of the other ideas you encountered in the readings as you wish. Put it in your sketchbook, upload the URL of the page to the <a href=\"https://q.utoronto.ca/courses/136326/assignments/246261\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">assignment</a>, and bring a hard copy to class.  Draw on your readings, last year&#39;s design history books (<a href=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1EQJXw-zStIFmflPkDbt21vcWhX2uv6vKgZ70m48dbtY/edit?usp=sharing\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">book 1</a> and <a href=\"https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/14_e_He3ZutR3rqvsYfWvjgHHglc0a8v6T0a5XGzGlEc/edit?usp=sharing\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">book 2</a>), further research, etc.  <a href=\"https://q.utoronto.ca/courses/136326/assignments/246261\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Submit</a> the URL of the wiki page so we can know you&#39;ve completed this.</p>\n<h3>Readings</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Selections from <a href=\"https://q.utoronto.ca/courses/136326/pages/mcdermott-design-the-key-concepts-selections\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">McDermott, Design: The Key Concepts</a></li>\n<li><ol start=\"3\">\n<li>BBC, In Our Time (2006) <a href=\"https://www.bbc.co.uk/sounds/play/p003c19x\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">&quot;The Great Exhibition of 1851&quot;</a> (28m)</li>\n</ol>\n</li>\n<li>Markovits on <a href=\"https://www.khanacademy.org/partner-content/wi-phi/wiphi-value-theory/wiphi-ethics/v/utilitarianism-part-1\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Utilitarianism</a> via Khan Academy (5m)</li>\n<li>Deutsche Welle (2019), &quot;Bauhaus World&quot; <a href=\"https://www.dw.com/en/top-stories/100-years-of-bauhaus/s-46784858\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Blog Post</a>, Video  <a href=\"https://youtu.be/rg3X1vZN5TA\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Part 1</a> (42m), <a href=\"https://youtu.be/LW1415Ddf8c\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Part II</a> (42m), <a href=\"https://youtu.be/2uVWAS6Q6AY\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Part III</a> (42m)</li>\n<li>Muraben, Billie (2017), <a href=\"https://www.itsnicethat.com/features/ulm-model-inge-scholl-otil-aicher-essay-230117\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">&quot;The Ulm Model: a school and its pursuit of a critical design practice&quot;</a> on It&#39;s Nice That (2300 wds)</li>\n<li>Malmö University (2018) <a href=\"https://medium.com/@medea/design-democracy-and-participation-exploring-the-scandinavian-participatory-design-tradition-67dda92ba675\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">&quot;Design, Democracy and Participation: Exploring the Scandinavian Participatory Design Tradition,&quot;</a> lecture by Pelle Ehn. <a href=\"https://youtu.be/g4xofWbhVu8\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Part 1</a> (33m), <a href=\"https://youtu.be/YYhNAkMTAuM\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Part II</a> (36m), <a href=\"https://youtu.be/W2uiYTiWIY8\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Part 3</a> (42m)</li>\n<li>parc (2019), <a href=\"https://www.parc.com/about-parc/parc-history/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">&quot;PARC History Timeline&quot;</a></li>\n<li>ABC Nightline (1999), &quot;<a href=\"https://youtu.be/izjhx17NuSE\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">The Deep Dive</a>&quot;  (22m) or shorter versions:<a href=\"https://youtu.be/M66ZU2PCIcM\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">8m</a>, <a href=\"https://youtu.be/W6EgoiPxNDs\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">15m</a></li>\n</ol>\n<h3>References and Further Reading</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Official Record (1851), <a href=\"http://resource.library.utoronto.ca/eir/EIRdetail.cfm?Resources__ID=2340380\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">&quot;Memorandum by the Prince Consort as to disposal of the surplus from the Great Exhibition of 1851&quot;</a></li>\n<li>Dickinson (1852), <a href=\"http://resource.library.utoronto.ca/eir/EIRdetail.cfm?Resources__ID=2336948\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">&quot;Dickinson&#39;s comprehensive pictures of The Great Exhibition of 1851&quot;</a></li>\n<li>MOMA (2011) <a href=\"https://www.moma.org/interactives/exhibitions/2010/counter_space/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">&quot;Counter Space: Design and the Modern Kitchen&quot;</a>;</li>\n<li>Werkbund archiv <a href=\"https://www.museumderdinge.org/exhibitions/permanent-collection-open-storage/frankfurt-kitchen\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">&quot;Frankfurt Kitchen&quot;</a></li>\n<li>&quot;<a href=\"https://web.stanford.edu/dept/SUL/sites/mac/parc.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">The Xerox PARC Visit</a>&quot; in the <a href=\"https://web.stanford.edu/dept/SUL/sites/mac/index.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Making the Macintosh: Technology and Culture in Silicon Valley</a> project</li>\n<li>Gladwell, Malcolm. 2011. &quot;<a href=\"https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2011/05/16/creation-myth\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Creation Myth: Xerox PARC, Apple, and the truth about innovation</a>.&quot; The New Yorker, May 16, 2011 Issue**</li>\n</ol>\n",
    "moreURL": "https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/e/2PACX-1vRRl_qg6V40GV6RtJ4A_yPAfV3TqsvRrRJSPwEDYvTTFmRNYiLD0W4A31h2pUROg4QrH3oVNciHP_Ww/pubembed?start=false&loop=false&delayms=3000"
